author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: I just hate to see it genuinely. I feel so passionately about it. I know there’s points of like artists getting exposure and profits and vendors having their own agenda but that to me makes me more nervous bc I can’t properly research where my shit I’m buying is coming from. Idk

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text:
I know not a lot of people care about this kind of thing, but I care so much about the environment and people. 

I have more in common with those that are homeless than the people buying tupac shirts for $1100 just because. 

I’m vegetarian primarily bc of my environmental impact

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text:
Their website says there are some $5-$10 racks but don’t expect thrifting prices bc these items are meant for vintage collectors. 

I found an Indiana University crew neck from like 2012 for $60.

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: In fact, after doing some research, the event was made to allow vintage collectors to gain access to “street wear” and to introduce it to the vintage scene. So basically, gentrification lmfao.

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: Like the dream would be that those clothes were so overpriced because the money was being donated to help the homeless community or to anyone in need but I fear this just isn’t the case

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: I know they took donations and such but honestly I have no clue whether or not those clothes are going to a cause or right back into thrift con. It would be cool if they could turn their blind eye to those in need and see how they could actually make an impact in their lives. Idk

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: How can you claim to be environmentally conscious but still falter into capitalism it makes no fucking sense my guy. I personally think it may be a tactic to make people feel better about what’s actually going on. This isn’t accessible to anyone without a disposable income.

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: I struggled thinking of the amount of waste from fast fashion and the sheer amount of clothes being produced and sold and how thrift con seemingly is about being resourceful and environmentally conscious but.. bro why was everything so expensive??

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: I felt weird when I was there and I was like ??? Is this wrong?? And my conclusion is yes it is very wrong :)

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: Why was there a Tupac shirt for $1100?? Did Tupac himself wear this shit? Like bitch

author: ❀ Achy Jakey Heart ❀
text: Ok my conclusion is that thrift con is as a disgusting display of gentrification and I never want to accidentally be apart of something like that again but I AM happy that what I did get was from an independent artist and something made from recycled materials
